Regression Analysis: Sales Revenue Prediction¶

Objective:¶

SuperKart is an organization that owns a chain of supermarkets and food marts providing a wide range of products. They want to predict the future sales revenue of its different outlets so that they can strategize their sales operation across different tier cities and plan their inventory accordingly. To achieve this purpose, SuperKart has hired a data science firm, shared the sales records of its various outlets for the previous quarter, and asked the firm to come up with a suitable model to predict the total sales of the stores for the upcoming quarter.

Data Variables:¶

The data contains the different attributes of the various products and stores. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • Product_Id - unique identifier of each product, each identifier having two letters at the beginning followed by a number.
  • Product_Weight - the weight of each product
  • Product_Sugar_Content - sugar content of each product like low sugar, regular, and no sugar
  • Product_Allocated_Area - the ratio of the allocated display area of each product to the total display area of all the products in a store
  • Product_Type - broad category for each product like meat, snack foods, hard drinks, dairy, canned, soft drinks, health and hygiene, baking goods, bread, breakfast, frozen foods, fruits and vegetables, household, seafood, starchy foods, others
  • Product_MRP - maximum retail price of each product
  • Store_Id - unique identifier of each store
  • Store_Establishment_Year - the year in which the store was established
  • Store_Size - the size of the store depending on sq. feet like high, medium, and low
  • Store_Location_City_Type - the type of city in which the store is located like Tier 1, Tier 2, and Tier 3. Tier 1 consists of cities where the standard of living is comparatively higher than its Tier 2 and Tier 3 counterparts.
  • Store_Type - the type of store depending on the products that are being sold there like Departmental Store, Supermarket Type 1, Supermarket Type 2, and Food Mart
  • Product_Store_Sales_Total - total revenue generated by the sale of that particular product in that particular store

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

def labeled_barplot(df, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Horizontal barplot with count or percentage labels at the end of each bar.

    df: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of counts (default False)
    n: display top n categories (default all)
    """

    total = len(df[feature])  # total rows
    order = df[feature].value_counts().index[:n]  # order by frequency

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, max(5, len(order) * 0.5)))  # dynamic height
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=df,
        y=feature,
        order=order,
        palette="Set2"
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(100 * p.get_width() / total)
        else:
            label = p.get_width()

        x = p.get_width()   # bar length
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height() / 2  # bar center

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="left",  # place label to the right
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(5, 0),  # offset a little to the right
            textcoords="offset points"
        )

    plt.xlabel("Count" if not perc else "Percentage")
    plt.ylabel(feature)
    plt.show()

Observations:¶

The barplots highlight several notable patterns in the categorical variables.

  • A majority of products (55.7%) fall under the low-sugar category.
  • The most common product types are fruits and vegetables, snack foods, frozen foods, and dairy, indicating a concentration in everyday consumer staples.
  • Over half of the products are associated with a single store (OUT004), suggesting strong dependence on this location.
  • Medium-sized stores in Tier 2 cities account for the largest share (68.8%), pointing to a concentration of distribution in this segment.
  • Interestingly, Supermarket Type 2 represents the same proportion of products as the dominant store ID (OUT004), suggesting an overlap or alignment between store type and store-level distribution.

  • Product Weight and Product MRP appear correlated with each other. This suggests the need to formally test for multicollinearity in subsequent modeling steps, as it may affect the stability of regression coefficients.

from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

# Function to check VIF
def checking_vif(train):
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["feature"] = train.columns

    # Calculating VIF for each feature
    vif["VIF"] = [
        variance_inflation_factor(train.values, i) for i in range(len(train.columns))
    ]
    return vif

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

  1. Mean of residuals should be 0
  2. Normality of error terms
  3. Linearity of variables
  4. No heteroscedasticity

4. No heteroscedasticity¶

We will use Goldfeld–Quandt test to check homoscedasticity.

Null hypothesis : Residuals are homoscedastic

Alternate hypothesis : Residuals are heteroscedastic

In [85]:

In [86]:

 ('p-value', np.float64(0.9748584502497936))]
  • p-value is > 0.05, so we fail to Reject H0.The residuals are homoscedastic.

In [94]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Prepare data
df = pd.DataFrame({'Actual': y_test, 'Predicted': y_pred})
df['Residual'] = df['Predicted'] - df['Actual']
df['AbsResidual'] = np.abs(df['Residual'])

# Figure and style
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.set_style("whitegrid")
ax = plt.gca()

# Color gradient: green (under) → yellow → red (over)
cmap = plt.cm.RdYlGn_r
norm = plt.Normalize(-df['Residual'].max(), df['Residual'].max())
colors = cmap(norm(df['Residual'].values))

# Scatter points: size proportional to abs(residual)
sizes = 50 + (df['AbsResidual'] / df['AbsResidual'].max() * 150)

# Plot all points at once
scatter = ax.scatter(df['Actual'], df['Predicted'],
                     s=sizes, c=colors, alpha=0.7, edgecolors='none', zorder=3)

# Diagonal line (perfect predictions)
max_val = max(df['Actual'].max(), df['Predicted'].max())
min_val = min(df['Actual'].min(), df['Predicted'].min())
ax.plot([min_val, max_val], [min_val, max_val], linestyle='--', color='gray', lw=2, alpha=0.7, zorder=4)

# Titles and labels
ax.set_title("Predicted vs Actual Sales", fontsize=28, weight='bold', pad=20)
ax.set_xlabel("Actual Sales", fontsize=16)
ax.set_ylabel("Predicted Sales", fontsize=16)

# Annotate metrics
rmse = np.sqrt(np.mean(df['Residual']**2))
r2 = np.corrcoef(df['Actual'], df['Predicted'])[0,1]**2
ax.text(min_val + (max_val-min_val)*0.05, max_val - (max_val-min_val)*0.1,
        f'RMSE: {rmse:.0f}\nR²: {r2:.3f}',
        fontsize=14, weight='medium', color='black',
        bbox=dict(facecolor='white', alpha=0.8, boxstyle='round,pad=0.5'))

# Colorbar
sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=norm)
sm.set_array(df['Residual'].values)
cbar = plt.colorbar(sm, ax=ax)
cbar.set_label('Prediction Residual', fontsize=12)

# Ticks and spines
ax.tick_params(axis='both', labelsize=12)
sns.despine(ax=ax, left=False, bottom=False)

# Save figure
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("pred_vs_actual_gallery_style_fixed.png", dpi=300)
plt.show()

Conclusion:¶

Our linear regression model achieved strong performance, explaining ~83% of the variation in sales (R² = 0.83) with an RMSE of ~$434. Key drivers of sales include Product MRP and Product Weight, confirming that premium and heavier items generate higher revenue. Medium-sized stores outperform both small and large stores, while Tier 1 city locations consistently achieve stronger sales than Tier 2 or Tier 3. Among store types, Supermarket Type 1 outlets deliver the best results, whereas Food Marts underperform. The close agreement between training and test results indicates that the model generalizes well and is not overfitting.

The regression equation can be written by looking at the coefficients on the Model Summary report and allow us to translate these results in business strategy:

  • It quantifies how much sales increase or decrease with changes in product, store size, city tier, or store type.
  • Stocking higher MRP products can increase sales by about 3,018 per unit increase.
  • Opening a new medium-sized store may add $690 more sales on average compared to a large store.
  • Overall, the coefficients can provide clear guidance for inventory planning, store expansion, and marketing focus across different city tiers and store formats.
